### Constructors in Java

A constructor is a special method that initializes objects when they are created.

---

### Constructor Rules

- Same name as the class
- No return type (not even void)
- Called automatically when `new` is used
- Can be overloaded

---

### Types of Constructors

| Type | Description |
|------|-------------|
| Default constructor | No parameters, provided if no constructor defined |
| Parameterized constructor | Accepts arguments for initialization |
| Copy constructor | Creates object from another object |

---

### Constructor Overloading

```java
public class Car {
    String brand;
    int year;

    // No-arg constructor
    public Car() {
        brand = "Unknown";
        year = 0;
    }

    // Parameterized constructor
    public Car(String brand, int year) {
        this.brand = brand;
        this.year = year;
    }
}
```

---

### Constructor Chaining

One constructor can call another using `this()`:

```java
public Car() {
    this("Default", 2024);  // calls parameterized constructor
}
```

> **Key Point:** If you define any constructor, the default no-arg constructor is NOT automatically provided. Use `this()` to chain constructors; it must be the first statement in the constructor.

codeExample:
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Car car1 = new Car();
        Car car2 = new Car("Toyota", 2022);
        Car car3 = new Car("Honda");

        car1.display();
        car2.display();
        car3.display();
    }
}

class Car {
    String brand;
    int year;

    Car() {
        this("Unknown", 0);
    }

    Car(String brand) {
        this(brand, 2024);
    }

    Car(String brand, int year) {
        this.brand = brand;
        this.year = year;
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.println(brand + " - " + year);
    }
}
